1
00:00:46,090 --> 00:00:49,440
MORTDECAI:
As you may well know, I am many things.

2
00:00:49,540 --> 00:00:52,500
An arts dealer, an accomplished fencer,

3
00:00:52,600 --> 00:00:55,140
fair shot with most weapons.

4
00:00:55,240 --> 00:00:59,823
I am loved and respected
by all who know me...

5
00:01:00,120 --> 00:01:01,585
Slightly.

6
00:01:05,560 --> 00:01:06,660
But I have always felt

7
00:01:06,760 --> 00:01:08,900
there's something missing, you see.

8
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:11,300
Some final piece of my personal puzzle.

9
00:01:11,400 --> 00:01:14,900
I needed something bold, distinctive.

10
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:16,300
Ah, thank you.

11
00:01:16,400 --> 00:01:18,060
The work of art with which

12
00:01:18,160 --> 00:01:20,580
I could declare to the heavens,

13
00:01:20,680 --> 00:01:23,700
I am Lord Charlie Mortdecai,

14
00:01:23,800 --> 00:01:28,189
and this little bit of magic

15
00:01:28,640 --> 00:01:30,708
is my mustache.

16
00:01:34,920 --> 00:01:35,900
I see.

17
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:38,706
Shall we to business then, Fang?

18
00:01:39,920 --> 00:01:41,909
Would you mind?

19
00:01:44,600 --> 00:01:46,429
"Find," you said.

20
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:50,910
Mmm, and find, I have done.

21
00:01:59,960 --> 00:02:02,381
The Qianlong vase.

22
00:02:03,560 --> 00:02:06,180
Very, very rare.

23
00:02:06,280 --> 00:02:08,269
Low-fired with an immersion glaze?

24
00:02:09,040 --> 00:02:10,300
None of the southern

25
00:02:10,400 --> 00:02:11,900
Yangtze ceramics are low-fired.

26
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:14,700
But you know that. You're testing me.

27
00:02:14,800 --> 00:02:15,900
(GROANS)

28
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:19,380
I'm so terribly sorry. Mosquito.
You see it?

29
00:02:19,480 --> 00:02:20,580
(MORTDECAI CHUCKLES)

30
00:02:20,680 --> 00:02:22,900
Why don't you test the vase instead?

31
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:24,460
I am sure that you will agree

32
00:02:24,560 --> 00:02:26,900
it is a bargain at two million pounds.

33
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:28,829
Everyone knows you're broke.

34
00:02:29,920 --> 00:02:32,341
You will take one million.

35
00:02:32,920 --> 00:02:33,980
Ooh.

36
00:02:34,080 --> 00:02:36,786
Golly, that was a big one! (CHUCKLES)

37
00:02:38,880 --> 00:02:41,142
Well, have it your way, Fang.

38
00:02:41,560 --> 00:02:43,310
One million pounds.

39
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:47,866
I trust that you have, um,
brought the treasuries?

40
00:02:54,560 --> 00:02:56,549
I think I'll keep the money.

41
00:02:56,760 --> 00:02:58,021
And the vase.

42
00:02:58,440 --> 00:02:59,500
(MUMBLES)

43
00:02:59,600 --> 00:03:01,660
You cheated me in our last deal.

44
00:03:01,760 --> 00:03:03,021
(STAMMERING)

45
00:03:03,240 --> 00:03:06,230
I paid three million for that tapestry,

46
00:03:06,760 --> 00:03:09,784
then found out it is worth only one!

47
00:03:10,760 --> 00:03:12,140
(GRUNTS)

48
00:03:12,240 --> 00:03:13,620
(CHUCKLES)

49
00:03:13,720 --> 00:03:17,791
You took from me.
Now I will take from you.

50
00:03:19,800 --> 00:03:24,180
Now, you look here, Fang! Fat. Fang Fat.

51
00:03:24,280 --> 00:03:26,140
I'm an art dealer, not a charlatan.

52
00:03:26,240 --> 00:03:28,780
A rogue, perhaps, a scamp

53
00:03:28,880 --> 00:03:30,260
or scoundrel, I will grant you.

54
00:03:30,360 --> 00:03:34,020
But never an outright mountebank.

55
00:03:34,120 --> 00:03:35,221
Enough!

56
00:03:36,120 --> 00:03:37,506
You owe me.

57
00:03:37,760 --> 00:03:40,780
I believe a finger would be fair.
Don't you?

58
00:03:40,880 --> 00:03:42,186
No!

59
00:03:43,480 --> 00:03:44,661
Oh!

60
00:03:44,800 --> 00:03:45,901
Jock!

61
00:03:49,720 --> 00:03:52,107
I wouldn't, mate. I really wouldn't.

62
00:03:52,280 --> 00:03:53,427
(MORTDECAI YELPS)

63
00:03:54,160 --> 00:03:57,060
Jockie, thank heavens!
Where have you been, man?

64
00:03:57,160 --> 00:03:59,103
Right behind you as always, sir.

65
00:04:02,440 --> 00:04:03,780
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

66
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:10,704
(SCREAMING)

67
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:12,180
Ahh!

68
00:04:12,280 --> 00:04:13,791
(GRUNTING)

69
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:16,181
MORTDECAI: Jock!

70
00:04:17,520 --> 00:04:18,781
(GRUNTING)

71
00:04:20,080 --> 00:04:21,864
Well done, Jockie.

72
00:04:22,520 --> 00:04:24,304
It's a privilege, sir!

73
00:04:27,760 --> 00:04:29,589
(SCREAMING CONTINUES)

74
00:04:38,880 --> 00:04:40,391
(SCREAMS)

75
00:04:44,880 --> 00:04:46,141
Jock, you're ablaze!

76
00:04:48,320 --> 00:04:49,785
(GRUNTING)

77
00:04:55,680 --> 00:04:57,780
Well, I think our work here is done.

78
00:04:57,880 --> 00:04:59,505
- Time to go, sir.
- Ah.

79
00:04:59,640 --> 00:05:01,265
(SIRENS WAILING)

80
00:05:07,040 --> 00:05:10,300
MORTDECAI: Jock laid out
the state of our financial affairs.

81
00:05:10,400 --> 00:05:12,821
Basically, they involved debt.

82
00:05:13,040 --> 00:05:15,108
Massive, crushing debt.

83
00:05:16,200 --> 00:05:19,780
We hurried back to Mortdecai Manor,
where my beloved wife, Johanna,

84
00:05:19,880 --> 00:05:22,420
having heard of our financial distress,

85
00:05:22,520 --> 00:05:23,740
was arriving home

86
00:05:23,840 --> 00:05:26,307
to sell off some
of my prized possessions.

87
00:05:27,080 --> 00:05:29,581
Even my horsey picture was on the block.

88
00:05:31,040 --> 00:05:33,900
But I was hopeful my new moustache

89
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:35,220
would cheer her up.

90
00:05:35,320 --> 00:05:36,546
JOHANNA: Darling!

91
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:39,340
Oh, God, I missed you terribly.

92
00:05:39,440 --> 00:05:42,140
MORTDECAI: Johanna. Love of my life.

93
00:05:42,240 --> 00:05:43,740
Apple of my eye.

94
00:05:43,840 --> 00:05:44,820
I so wish you had been there.

95
00:05:44,920 --> 00:05:45,860
(SIGHS)

96
00:05:45,960 --> 00:05:48,420
Can you imagine the two of us

97
00:05:48,520 --> 00:05:50,020
in that frigid city,

98
00:05:50,120 --> 00:05:51,660
only our passions keeping us...

99
00:05:51,760 --> 00:05:54,386
Whoa! (LAUGHING) What is that?

100
00:05:54,680 --> 00:05:56,100
Just a little something I cooked up

101
00:05:56,200 --> 00:05:57,711
whilst you were away, my darling.

102
00:05:58,120 --> 00:06:01,180
I do believe it was Maggie Thatcher
who said that kissing a man without

103
00:06:01,280 --> 00:06:06,546
a moustache is rather like
eating an egg without salt.

104
00:06:06,720 --> 00:06:08,700
Oh, don't point that thing at me.

105
00:06:08,800 --> 00:06:09,881
Told ya.

106
00:06:11,360 --> 00:06:13,340
I have put no inconsiderable thought

107
00:06:13,440 --> 00:06:15,340
and effort into this endeavor.

108
00:06:15,440 --> 00:06:17,540
You see, the domain of a man's upper lip

109
00:06:17,640 --> 00:06:18,860
is his sovereign ground...

110
00:06:18,960 --> 00:06:20,460
You have five minutes to shave it off.

111
00:06:20,560 --> 00:06:25,063
Every Mortdecai man before me
had the same. Why can't I?

112
00:06:28,800 --> 00:06:30,700
Oh, I happen to be terribly fond of it,

113
00:06:30,800 --> 00:06:35,667
and I have had every intention
of seeing it through.

114
00:06:36,120 --> 00:06:39,190
You mean it's going to get bigger?

115
00:06:39,600 --> 00:06:42,021
It will come to fruition, yes.

116
00:06:42,320 --> 00:06:44,460
(CLICKS TONGUE) Oh, darling...

117
00:06:44,560 --> 00:06:45,946
MORTDECAI: Mmm.

118
00:06:46,640 --> 00:06:48,583
You really won't shave it off?

119
00:06:49,160 --> 00:06:50,700
Oh...

120
00:06:50,800 --> 00:06:53,580
I can't, my duck. Not at this juncture.

121
00:06:53,680 --> 00:06:56,431
It's not even fully corked. It's a baby.

122
00:06:57,280 --> 00:06:59,382
- Jock?
- Yes, madam?

123
00:06:59,520 --> 00:07:00,580
Please, will you make up

124
00:07:00,680 --> 00:07:02,740
the guest bedroom for Mr. Mortdecai?

125
00:07:02,840 --> 00:07:04,380
Already have, madam.

126
00:07:04,480 --> 00:07:06,500
And I shan't be having dinner
downstairs this evening.

127
00:07:06,600 --> 00:07:09,580
I'll just have a supper tray in my room.

128
00:07:09,680 --> 00:07:10,861
Very good, madam.

129
00:07:12,800 --> 00:07:14,106
JOHANNA: Oh...

130
00:07:14,360 --> 00:07:15,740
I do believe Jock has informed you

131
00:07:15,840 --> 00:07:19,420
that we are staring down
the barrel of insolvency.

132
00:07:19,520 --> 00:07:21,340
What do you plan to do about it?

133
00:07:21,440 --> 00:07:23,986
Right. Yes, well...

134
00:07:24,120 --> 00:07:28,066
That... Well... Quite.

135
00:07:28,200 --> 00:07:30,951
First thing we're doing
is selling off that Sheridan.

136
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:33,226
(MOANS)

137
00:07:34,680 --> 00:07:36,780
Oh, my sweet little love beast,

138
00:07:36,880 --> 00:07:39,940
I am sure that we will
come up with the necessary funds

139
00:07:40,040 --> 00:07:41,940
by the end of the month.
What is today, the fifth!

140
00:07:42,040 --> 00:07:43,300
The 26th, sir.

141
00:07:43,400 --> 00:07:44,700
All right. That gives us six...

142
00:07:44,800 --> 00:07:45,780
Four days, sir.

143
00:07:45,880 --> 00:07:47,420
Jock? Please can you take the Sheridan

144
00:07:47,520 --> 00:07:48,780
up to London in the morning?

145
00:07:48,880 --> 00:07:50,780
I'm entering it
in the Autumn Masters Auction.

146
00:07:50,880 --> 00:07:51,900
Right you are, madam.

147
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:53,860
Come, come. Let's not be rash.

148
00:07:53,960 --> 00:07:55,300
JOHANNA: Oh, hello, Poppet.

149
00:07:55,400 --> 00:07:57,980
We cannot go about selling off
family heirlooms willy-nilly.

150
00:07:58,080 --> 00:08:01,420
I'm afraid I shall have to
put my foot down, darling.

151
00:08:01,520 --> 00:08:02,667
Sorry?

152
00:08:03,400 --> 00:08:05,025
With your permission, of course.

153
00:08:07,560 --> 00:08:08,740
(SIGHS)

154
00:08:08,840 --> 00:08:11,750
Bugger it. Oh, there he is.

155
00:08:12,320 --> 00:08:13,501
Mmm.

156
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:15,980
She'll come around, Jock.
How could she not?

157
00:08:16,080 --> 00:08:17,784
She's only human, sir.

158
00:08:18,600 --> 00:08:20,660
MORTDECAI: A quick aside about Jock.

159
00:08:20,760 --> 00:08:23,431
In addition to being
my manservant and thug,

160
00:08:23,760 --> 00:08:26,300
he also maintains an enviable rate

161
00:08:26,400 --> 00:08:28,150
of sexual intercourse,

162
00:08:29,560 --> 00:08:32,180
which can be occasionally problematic.

163
00:08:32,280 --> 00:08:35,340
Recently, after we'd concluded
the sale of a painting

164
00:08:35,440 --> 00:08:37,383
to a wealthy turkey farmer...

165
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:39,020
(GUNSHOT)

166
00:08:39,120 --> 00:08:40,301
What was that?

167
00:08:42,120 --> 00:08:43,500
Get your head down, sir.

168
00:08:43,600 --> 00:08:45,340
What have you done now, man?

169
00:08:45,440 --> 00:08:46,660
Ohh!

170
00:08:46,760 --> 00:08:48,500
Onward, Jock! Onward!

171
00:08:48,600 --> 00:08:50,180
Don't shoot, farmer!

172
00:08:50,280 --> 00:08:52,223
Dad! What the hell are you doing?

173
00:08:54,280 --> 00:08:56,542
Jock! Jock, wait! Jock!

174
00:08:56,960 --> 00:08:58,540
I have me own apartment!

175
00:08:58,640 --> 00:09:01,980
Crikey, man! The farmer's daughter?

176
00:09:02,080 --> 00:09:04,100
I only gave her the once-over.

177
00:09:04,200 --> 00:09:05,500
Where do you find the time?

178
00:09:05,600 --> 00:09:07,384
Sorry, twice-over.

179
00:09:08,640 --> 00:09:11,980
MORTDECAI: Dear, sweet, simple Jock.

180
00:09:12,080 --> 00:09:14,421
Every man should have a Jock,
don't you think?

181
00:09:20,160 --> 00:09:23,264
Meanwhile, not far away,

182
00:09:23,760 --> 00:09:26,140
our fortunes were about
to become intertwined

183
00:09:26,240 --> 00:09:30,265
with one of the art
world's greatest mysteries.

184
00:09:33,480 --> 00:09:35,264
And a dead hag.

185
00:09:35,960 --> 00:09:36,900
(ARROW HISSING)

186
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:38,101
(GASPS)

187
00:09:40,680 --> 00:09:41,781
Bull's-eye.

188
00:09:51,520 --> 00:09:55,227
GARDENER: Miss Bronwen?
Everything all right?

189
00:10:26,120 --> 00:10:28,302
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

190
00:10:30,560 --> 00:10:32,071
Get back behind the tape!

191
00:10:32,880 --> 00:10:35,790
Excuse me. This is a crime scene.

192
00:10:37,640 --> 00:10:38,901
Hello?

193
00:10:39,800 --> 00:10:41,260
Who is this guy?

194
00:10:41,360 --> 00:10:42,580
You and your men have done

195
00:10:42,680 --> 00:10:44,980
an admirable job stomping
all over the place.

196
00:10:45,080 --> 00:10:47,148
Your services are no longer required.

197
00:10:49,040 --> 00:10:51,188
Sorry, Inspector Martland, sir.

198
00:10:52,720 --> 00:10:54,900
Sorry, sir. I had no idea, sir.

199
00:10:55,000 --> 00:10:56,340
(CAMERA CLICKING)

200
00:10:58,240 --> 00:10:59,980
Can I have all Thames Valley
police officers

201
00:11:00,080 --> 00:11:01,300
back in their cars, please?

202
00:11:01,400 --> 00:11:03,821
There's been a jurisdictional change.

203
00:11:13,240 --> 00:11:15,500
That painting could be
anywhere by now, sir.

204
00:11:15,600 --> 00:11:18,300
Yes, I suppose it could.

205
00:11:18,400 --> 00:11:20,660
You know we're going to have
to ring him, don't you, sir?

206
00:11:20,760 --> 00:11:22,340
No, I do not know that, Maurice.

207
00:11:22,440 --> 00:11:24,660
No one knows the filthy underside
of the art world better than he, sir.

208
00:11:24,760 --> 00:11:26,544
He is the filthy underside.

209
00:11:27,520 --> 00:11:28,500
(SIGHS)

210
00:11:28,600 --> 00:11:30,384
Why did it have to be art?

211
00:11:32,600 --> 00:11:34,987
MORTDECAI: Inspector Alastair Martland.

212
00:11:35,120 --> 00:11:36,700
Ml5.

213
00:11:36,800 --> 00:11:38,940
Martland and I met at Oxford.

214
00:11:39,040 --> 00:11:40,420
Once in a while I provide him

215
00:11:40,520 --> 00:11:41,940
with some off-the-record help

216
00:11:42,040 --> 00:11:45,140
with the seedier side of art collecting.

217
00:11:45,240 --> 00:11:51,029
And in exchange, he gives me
a wide berth to ply my craft.

218
00:11:51,480 --> 00:11:55,301
He is also desperately in love
with my wife.

219
00:11:55,800 --> 00:11:56,940
Rather annoying, really.

220
00:11:57,040 --> 00:11:58,221
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

221
00:11:58,600 --> 00:11:59,700
What?

222
00:11:59,800 --> 00:12:01,820
Inspector Martland, sir.

223
00:12:01,920 --> 00:12:03,909
What does that blighter want?

224
00:12:04,720 --> 00:12:07,180
Tell him to ring back when my marriage
isn't falling apart.

225
00:12:07,280 --> 00:12:08,660
No, he's here, sir.

226
00:12:08,760 --> 00:12:10,220
He is?

227
00:12:10,320 --> 00:12:12,741
Oh, all right. Wheel him in.

228
00:12:13,400 --> 00:12:14,740
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

229
00:12:15,480 --> 00:12:16,460
Don't get up.

230
00:12:16,560 --> 00:12:18,344
I wasn't going to.

231
00:12:19,560 --> 00:12:22,060
Beware the carafe on the top shelf.

232
00:12:22,160 --> 00:12:23,341
It contains water.

233
00:12:24,120 --> 00:12:25,220
Ignoring some of the more

234
00:12:25,320 --> 00:12:26,820
inviting bottles on the drinks tray,

235
00:12:26,920 --> 00:12:28,900
he reached underneath
for the big decanter,

236
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:30,140
and poured himself

237
00:12:30,240 --> 00:12:34,020
a gross amount of what
he thought was my Taylor '31.

238
00:12:34,120 --> 00:12:36,340
Score one for Mortdecai,

239
00:12:36,440 --> 00:12:38,580
for I had filled it with an invalid port

240
00:12:38,680 --> 00:12:40,900
of unbelievable nastiness.

241
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:42,340
Oh, excellent.

242
00:12:42,440 --> 00:12:43,740
Score two.

243
00:12:43,840 --> 00:12:45,783
MARTLAND: Bit of cheese to go with that?

244
00:12:46,920 --> 00:12:48,863
I should think the special one, Jock.

245
00:13:02,520 --> 00:13:04,748
What is that infernal thing on your lip?

246
00:13:06,200 --> 00:13:07,825
Is there a purpose to your presence?

247
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:10,020
You're in the hole
to Her Majesty's government

248
00:13:10,120 --> 00:13:12,985
to the tune
of eight million quid, old boy.

249
00:13:13,200 --> 00:13:17,385
I had no idea I was so deep
in Her Majesty's hole.

250
00:13:18,040 --> 00:13:19,949
(JOCK GRUNTING)

251
00:13:21,800 --> 00:13:24,780
God, oh, God, oh, God, oh, God...

252
00:13:24,880 --> 00:13:26,220
(EXHALING SHARPLY)

253
00:13:29,560 --> 00:13:31,185
(WHIMPERING)

254
00:13:37,080 --> 00:13:38,511
(EXHALES)

255
00:13:39,320 --> 00:13:40,831
That's not natural.

256
00:13:43,760 --> 00:13:45,191
What do you think?

257
00:13:46,320 --> 00:13:47,626
Ugh...

258
00:13:48,520 --> 00:13:50,980
I think this woman has need
of a chiropractor.

259
00:13:51,080 --> 00:13:53,220
Bronwen Fellworthy, Oxford art restorer.

260
00:13:53,320 --> 00:13:54,467
Did you know her?

261
00:13:54,600 --> 00:13:55,826
Slightly.

262
00:13:56,520 --> 00:13:59,140
I do recall a vague memory
of her having once,

263
00:13:59,240 --> 00:14:01,547
involuntarily, one would hope,

264
00:14:02,760 --> 00:14:04,420
releasing a fart

265
00:14:04,520 --> 00:14:06,987
of such frightening power and timbre

266
00:14:07,720 --> 00:14:09,580
that I feared she had done herself

267
00:14:09,680 --> 00:14:11,140
a horrible mischief.

268
00:14:11,240 --> 00:14:12,501
Cheese.

269
00:14:13,240 --> 00:14:14,501
